The paper analyzes the Tendermint blockchain protocol, which is a distributed system and falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also focuses on the security aspects of the protocol, which makes it relevant to the sub-category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR). The analysis involves identifying algorithmic principles, which can be considered as an aspect of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also considers different communication models and adversaries, which are relevant to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI), respectively.
